## Section 4: Device-interrupt delivery seam list (Increment 2)

This is net-new plumbing. It does NOT reuse the interval timer's
b_irq<2> aggregation: the timer rides i_intim_l -> b_irq<2> (EI level
22) via a direct cpu-field poke and bypasses DRIR/DIM. COM1 rides the
device path: DRIR<55> -> AND DIMn -> DIRn -> b_irq<1> (EI level 23).

Naming hazard -- two registers both called "IER," both must be open:
- UART IER (offset 0x3F9): the 16550 enable, RX+THR (0x03 observed).
- CPU HW_IER (IPR 0x010A), EIEN field: the 21264 external-interrupt
  enable. Device line is EI level 23; per the 2026-05-19 Phase D map
  (irqLevel -> IER bit via 57 - irqLevel) that is bit 34 = EIEN<1>.
Name them apart in code/comments (e.g. uartIer vs cpu.ier / EIEN).
A COM1 interrupt that sets DRIR but finds EIEN<1> masked is correctly
dropped; if the two IERs are conflated in the trace this will read as
a bug.

Seam-by-seam (each edit gets a header FILE N / FUNCTION / CHANGE block
and an inline comment at the changed line, per the house rule):

```
SEAM 1  UART -> Cchip assert
  When (uart_int_pending AND MCR.OUT2) rises, call the Cchip
  device-interrupt assert for the COM1 line; when it falls, deassert.
  OUT2 is the board-level delivery gate (Section 2); it gates this
  assert only, never the IIR computation.
  raiseDeviceInterrupt(55):  DRIR |= (1 << 55)
  lowerDeviceInterrupt(55):  DRIR &= ~(1 << 55)
  File: [COWORK: UART model .cpp, line N]
  Calls into: chipsetLib/TsunamiCchip.h  [COWORK: line N]

SEAM 2  Cchip DRIR/DIM re-eval -> b_irq<1>
  On DRIR change OR DIMn write, recompute per CPU:
    DIRn   = DRIR & DIMn
    irq1   = (DIRn & 0x00ffffffffffffff) != 0   // device, level 23
    irq0   = (DIRn & 0xfc00000000000000) != 0   // error,  level 30
  Drive the device EI request line from irq1.
  NOTE: AXPBox stores DIM without re-running the eval (it re-evals on
  the next interrupt() call). V4 SHOULD re-eval on the DIM write too,
  for predictable side-effect ordering (V4 determinism mandate).
  File: chipsetLib/TsunamiCchip.h  [COWORK: read/write switch line N]

SEAM 3  EI request latch -> canAcceptInterrupt -> divert
  Device line presented as EI level 23. canAcceptInterrupt(23) gates on
  (cpu.ier & EIEN<1>) AND IPL-permits AND NOT palMode. On accept, the
  existing divert mechanism (the one the timer exercises) delivers.
  File: Machine.cpp  [COWORK: canAcceptInterrupt, near the 694-698
  region noted in the profile; verify the IRQ-to-IPL map row for
  device=23]

SEAM 4  HW_IER storage (already landed 2026-05-19 Phase D)
  Confirm execHwMfpr/execHwMtpr HW_IER read/store cpu.ier and that
  EIEN<1> (bit 34) is reachable. No change expected; verify only.
  File: palBoxLib/grains/PalEntries.cpp  [COWORK: verify line N]
```

